SIMPLE: grudge
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Grudge
<hw>Grudge</hw> <pr>(gr⟦ucr⟧j)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Grudger</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Grudging</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>grutchen</ets>, <ets>gruchen</ets>, <ets>grochen</ets>, to murmur,
grumble, OF. <ets>grochier</ets>, <ets>grouchier</ets>,
<ets>grocier</ets>, <ets>groucier</ets>; cf. Icel. <ets>krytja</ets> to
murmur, <ets>krutr</ets> a murmur, or E. <ets>grunt</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To look upon with desire to possess or to appropriate;
to envy (one) the possession of; to begrudge; to covet; to give with
reluctance; to desire to get back again; -- followed by the direct
object only, or by both the direct and indirect objects.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tis not in thee To <qex>grudge</qex> my pleasures, to cut off my
train.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have often heard the Presbyterians say, they did not
<qex>grudge</qex> us our employments.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They have <qex>grudged</qex> us contribution.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To hold or harbor with malicious disposition or
purpose; to cherish enviously.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Perish they⟦br⟧
That <qex>grudge</qex> one thought against your majesty !</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grudge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Grudge
<hw>Grudge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be
covetous or envious; to show discontent; to murmur; to complain; to
repine; to be unwilling or reluctant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Grudge</qex> not one against another.</q> <rj><qau>James v.
9. </qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He eats his meat without <qex>grudging</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To feel compunction or grief.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bp. Fisher.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grudge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Grudge
<hw>Grudge</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Sullen malice or
malevolence; cherished malice, enmity, or dislike; ill will; an old
cause of hatred or quarrel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Esau had conceived a mortal <qex>grudge</qex> and enmity against
his brother Jacob.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The feeling may not be envy; it may not be imbittered by a
<qex>grudge</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor. </qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Slight symptom of disease.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our shaken monarchy, that now lies . . . struggling against the
<qex>grudges</qex> of more dreaded calamities.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Pique; aversion; dislike; ill will; hatred;
spite. See <er>Pique</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grudgeful</ent>⟦br⟧
